---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import { articleSchema, faqSchema } from '../../../data/schema.js';
import { topics } from '../../../data/ages.js';

const title = '12–18 Month Old Development: What to Expect';
const description = 'The transition from baby to toddler is a major milestone. Between 12 and 18 months, your child will likely take their first steps, say their first words, and begin to explore the world with new independence.';

const faqs = [
  {
    question: 'When should my child start walking?',
    answer: 'While many babies take their first steps around their first birthday, the CDC recently updated its milestones to reflect that walking without support is a milestone 75% of children reach by 18 months. If your child is not walking by 18 months, consult your pediatrician.',
  },
  {
    question: 'How many words should an 18-month-old say?',
    answer: 'By 18 months, most toddlers can say at least three words other than "mama" or "dada." They are also beginning to follow simple one-step directions without any gestures, like "Give me the toy."',
  },
  {
    question: 'Is it normal for my toddler to throw tantrums already?',
    answer: 'Yes. Between 12 and 18 months, toddlers begin to develop their own will but lack the verbal skills to express their frustrations. This often results in tantrums. Staying calm and providing simple labels for their emotions can help.',
  },
  {
    question: 'When should I switch from a bottle to a cup?',
    answer: 'The AAP recommends transitioning from a bottle to a cup by 12 to 18 months. By 18 months, many toddlers can drink from an open cup (with some spilling).',
  },
];

const aSchema = articleSchema({
  title,
  description,
  url: 'https://ageexpectations.com/ages/12-18-months/',
});
const fSchema = faqSchema(faqs);
---
<BaseLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  articleSchema={aSchema}
  faqSchema={fSchema}
  breadcrumbs={[
    { label: '12–18 Months' },
  ]}
>
  <h1>12–18 Month Old Development: What to Expect</h1>

  <p>The transition from "infant" to "toddler" happens somewhere between 12 and 18 months. This is a period of rapid physical growth and even faster cognitive development. Your child is moving from being a passive observer to an active, often vocal, participant in the family.</p>

  <p>This overview covers the major developmental shifts for toddlers in this exciting transition period, based on the latest research and guidelines from the AAP and CDC.</p>

  <h2>Explore 12–18 Month Topics</h2>
  <div class="topic-grid">
    {topics.map(topic => (
      <a href={`/ages/12-18-months/${topic.slug}/`} class="topic-card">{topic.label}</a>
    ))}
  </div>

  <h2>Physical Development: On the Move</h2>

  <p>The most visible changes during this stage are physical. Most children become "toddlers" in the literal sense during these months.</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Walking:</strong> Most children are walking by 15 to 18 months. They may still be "wobbly" and use a wide-based gait for balance.</li>
    <li><strong>Climbing:</strong> Once they can walk, many toddlers immediately try to climb onto furniture or up stairs (usually on hands and knees at first).</li>
    <li><strong>Fine Motor:</strong> Your toddler is learning to use tools. They may try to use a spoon, scribble with a crayon, or "help" you by holding a phone to their ear.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Language and Communication: First Words</h2>

  <p>Receptive language (what they understand) usually outpaces expressive language (what they can say) during this period.</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Vocabulary:</strong> By 18 months, expect at least 3-5 specific words. They also understand many more nouns and simple commands.</li>
    <li><strong>Gestures:</strong> Toddlers use pointing to show you things they find interesting, which is a key social-communication milestone.</li>
    <li><strong>Following Directions:</strong> They should be able to follow simple instructions like "Sit down" or "Bring me the ball" without you needing to point.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Social and Emotional: Seeking Independence</h2>

  <p>The 12-18 month stage is the beginning of "autonomy." Your toddler is realizing they are a separate person from you.</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Social Referencing:</strong> They will often move away from you to explore but will look back to see if you are still there and if you look "safe."</li>
    <li><strong>Imitation:</strong> This is a peak time for copying your actions—sweeping, "talking" on the phone, or pretending to cook.</li>
    <li><strong>Self-Awareness:</strong> They may begin to recognize themselves in the mirror or in photos.</li>
  </ul>

  <div class="faq-section">
    <h2>Is This Normal? Common Questions About 12–18 Month Development</h2>
    {faqs.map(faq => (
      <div class="faq-item">
        <p class="faq-question">{faq.question}</p>
        <p class="faq-answer">{faq.answer}</p>
      </div>
    ))}
  </div>

  <div class="callout">
    <h2>When to Talk to Your Pediatrician</h2>
    <p>The 12-month and 18-month well-child visits are critical. The 18-month visit often includes a formal autism screening (M-CHAT). Contact your doctor if your child:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Is not walking by 18 months</li>
      <li>Does not point to show things to others</li>
      <li>Loses skills they once had (like words or social interest)</li>
      <li>Does not gain at least a few new words between 12 and 18 months</li>
      <li>Does not notice or mind when a caregiver leaves or returns</li>
    </ul>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
